<Layout title="Food & Wine Pairing Fundamentals" description="Practical principles for pairing wine with food — forget the old rules, here's how it actually works.">
  <section class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-6 py-20">
    <p class="text-amber-600 font-medium tracking-wider uppercase text-sm mb-3">Learn</p>
    <h1 class="font-display text-4xl md:text-5xl font-bold text-stone-900 mb-6">Food & Wine Pairing Fundamentals</h1>
    <p class="text-stone-500 text-sm mb-8">By Roberto Carli, CMS · 11 min read</p>

    <div class="prose prose-stone max-w-none">
      <p class="text-lg text-stone-600 leading-relaxed">"Red wine with meat, white wine with fish." You've heard this rule a thousand times. And while it's not entirely wrong, it's so reductive that it's practically useless. Real food and wine pairing is more nuanced — and far more rewarding — than a two-part formula.</p>

      <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold text-stone-900 mt-10">The Three Principles</h2>

      <h3 class="font-display text-xl font-bold text-stone-900 mt-6">1. Match Weight for Weight</h3>
      <p>The single most important pairing principle is matching the <em>body</em> of the wine to the <em>richness</em> of the dish. A delicate Pinot Grigio gets bulldozed by a heavily sauced beef stew. A massive Napa Cabernet overwhelms a piece of poached sole.</p>
      <p>Think of it as a volume knob: light dishes need light wines, rich dishes need full-bodied wines, and everything in between should be calibrated accordingly.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Light food + Light wine:</strong> Salads, ceviche, steamed fish → Sauvignon Blanc, Muscadet, Vinho Verde</li>
        <li><strong>Medium food + Medium wine:</strong> Roast chicken, pasta with tomato sauce, grilled salmon → Pinot Noir, Côtes du Rhône, Rosé</li>
        <li><strong>Rich food + Bold wine:</strong> Braised short ribs, aged cheese, grilled ribeye → Barolo, Cabernet Sauvignon, Malbec</li>
      </ul>

      <h3 class="font-display text-xl font-bold text-stone-900 mt-6">2. Complement or Contrast</h3>
      <p>There are two valid strategies and both work beautifully:</p>
      <p><strong>Complement:</strong> Mirror the flavors in the dish. Earthy mushroom risotto with an earthy Pinot Noir. Lemony seafood with a citrusy Sauvignon Blanc. The wine and food echo each other, creating harmony.</p>
      <p><strong>Contrast:</strong> Create tension that resolves pleasantly. Spicy Thai curry with an off-dry Riesling — the sweetness tames the heat. Salty blue cheese with sweet Sauternes — the opposites elevate each other. Rich, fatty dishes with high-acid wines — the acid cuts through the richness like a knife.</p>

      <h3 class="font-display text-xl font-bold text-stone-900 mt-6">3. Consider the Sauce, Not Just the Protein</h3>
      <p>A chicken breast can be paired with almost anything depending on how it's prepared. Chicken in a cream sauce? Oaked Chardonnay. Chicken with chimichurri? A herbaceous Sauvignon Blanc. Chicken tikka masala? An aromatic Gewürztraminer or off-dry Chenin Blanc.</p>
      <p>The sauce, seasoning, and cooking method matter more than the protein itself. This is why the old "red with meat, white with fish" rule breaks down — grilled tuna with a red wine reduction pairs brilliantly with Pinot Noir.</p>

      <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold text-stone-900 mt-10">Specific Pairing Scenarios</h2>

      <h3 class="font-display text-xl font-bold text-stone-900 mt-6">Pizza and Pasta</h3>
      <p>Italian food is remarkably wine-friendly because Italian wines evolved alongside the cuisine. For tomato-based sauces, reach for a wine with good acidity to match the tomatoes: Chianti Classico (Sangiovese), Barbera d'Alba, or a Montepulciano d'Abruzzo. For cream-based pastas, try a medium-bodied white like Verdicchio or a light red like Dolcetto.</p>

      <h3 class="font-display text-xl font-bold text-stone-900 mt-6">Spicy Food</h3>
      <p>Heat from chili peppers amplifies the perception of alcohol and tannin — so big, tannic reds with spicy food are a disaster. Instead, go for wines with low alcohol, a touch of sweetness, and bright acidity: off-dry Riesling, Gewürztraminer, sparkling wine, or a light Gamay served slightly chilled.</p>

      <h3 class="font-display text-xl font-bold text-stone-900 mt-6">Grilled Meats</h3>
      <p>Charring from the grill adds bitterness and smokiness that pairs well with wines that have similar qualities: smoky Syrah from the Northern Rhône, oaked Tempranillo from Rioja, or a bold Zinfandel with its peppery spice.</p>

      <h3 class="font-display text-xl font-bold text-stone-900 mt-6">Cheese</h3>
      <p>Forget the myth that red wine is best with cheese. Many cheeses actually pair better with white wine or sparkling. Fresh goat cheese loves Sancerre (Sauvignon Blanc). Aged Comté shines with Vin Jaune or oaked Chardonnay. Blue cheese craves sweetness — Port, Sauternes, or late-harvest Riesling. The only cheese that genuinely prefers big reds is aged, hard cheese like Parmigiano-Reggiano (try it with Barolo).</p>

      <h3 class="font-display text-xl font-bold text-stone-900 mt-6">Dessert</h3>
      <p>The cardinal rule: the wine should be sweeter than the dessert. A dry Champagne with wedding cake is a disaster (the cake makes the wine taste sour). Instead: Moscato d'Asti with fruit tart, Brachetto d'Acqui with chocolate-dipped strawberries, Tawny Port with crème brûlée, or Pedro Ximénez sherry drizzled directly over vanilla ice cream.</p>

      <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold text-stone-900 mt-10">The Universal Pairing Cheat Sheet</h2>
      <p>When in doubt, these wines pair with almost anything:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Champagne / sparkling wine</strong> — acidity and bubbles cleanse the palate between bites; works with everything from oysters to fried chicken</li>
        <li><strong>Dry rosé</strong> — bridges the gap between red and white; handles salads, grilled meats, and spice</li>
        <li><strong>Pinot Noir</strong> — light enough for fish, substantial enough for poultry and game; the Swiss Army knife of reds</li>
        <li><strong>Off-dry Riesling</strong> — sweetness tames spice, acidity cuts richness; stunning versatility from sushi to Thai to barbecue</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold text-stone-900 mt-10">The Only Rule That Matters</h2>
      <p>If you enjoy the combination, it's a good pairing. Full stop. Pairing guidelines exist to increase the probability of a great experience, but taste is personal. I've seen people genuinely love Cabernet with sushi. Who am I to argue?</p>
      <p>That said, if you want to <em>maximize</em> the synergy between what's on your plate and what's in your glass, the principles above will serve you well 90% of the time. And for the other 10%? That's where the fun experiments happen.</p>
